ramen200<- ramen[complete.cases(ramen),] %>%

  filter(productCount>200)

Add new column for distribution groups
ramen200_grade<- ramen200 %>% ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(grade = if_else(stars==0,"zero", 
                         if_else(stars==5, "full", as.character(stars%/%1))))

Create charts using ggplot

[Anatomy of ggplot] (https://bookdown.org/jkylearmstrong/Fundamentals-of-Data-Wrangling/the-anatomy-of-ggplot.html){target=_blank}

We are using ggplot2 package.

library(ggplot2)
Basic functions to create a chart

In ggplot, you create a chart as if you add layers using + on a canvas.

  1. ggplot() : creates blank canvas with data and variable setting (default for all layers)
  2. geom_xxx() : draws geometries (shapes) representing the values in your data
  3. labs() : title and labels
  4. theme_xxx() : theme of the overall chart.

When you choose a type of graph, these are the geom_xxx()s:

  • Histograms - geom_histogram()
  • Bar charts - geom_bar() or geom_col()
  • Box plots - geom_boxplot()
  • Points (e.g.scatter plots) - geom_point()
  • Line graphs - geom_line() or geom_path()
  • Trend lines - geom_smooth()

When you specify aspects related to your variables, put it inside aes()

If it is constant value, which is independent of your variables (e.g., 1,2,3,, red, black,), put it outside aes()

Lets try with a simpler data, mtcars.

  • scatter plot showing relationship between x=hp and y=mpg
mtcars
mtcars %>% ggplot(aes(x= hp, y=mpg))

mtcars%>% ggplot(aes(x= hp, y=mpg)) + geom_point()

mtcars%>% ggplot(aes(x= hp, y=mpg, color=cyl)) + geom_point()

mtcars%>% ggplot(aes(x= hp, y=mpg, color=as.factor(cyl))) + 
  geom_point()

mtcars%>% ggplot(aes(x= hp, y=mpg, shape=as.factor(cyl))) + 
  geom_point()

mtcars%>% ggplot(aes(x= hp, y=mpg, shape=as.factor(cyl), color="red")) + 
  geom_point()

mtcars%>% ggplot(aes(x= hp, y=mpg, shape=as.factor(cyl))) + 
  geom_point(color="red", size=4) + geom_point(shape=4)

mtcars%>% ggplot(aes(x= hp, y=mpg, color=as.factor(cyl))) + 
  geom_point(size=2) + 
  labs(title = "Relationship betweein hp and mpg", color="cyl")

mtcars%>% ggplot(aes(as.factor(cyl), mpg)) + 
  geom_boxplot(fill="yellow")

mtcars%>% ggplot(aes(as.factor(cyl), mpg)) + 
  geom_boxplot(fill="yellow") +
  geom_point(shape = 4)

mtcars%>% ggplot(aes(as.factor(cyl), mpg)) + 
  geom_boxplot(fill="yellow") +
  geom_point(shape = 4) +
  labs(title="Two layers together", x="cyl")

mtcars%>% ggplot(aes(as.factor(cyl), mpg)) +

Now, getting back to our data, lets create a stacked bar chart.

  • geom_bar(aes(stat="count")) (by default): shows frequency. y variable is not needed
  • geom_bar(aes(stat="identity")) : shows
ramen200_grade %>% ggplot(aes(country)) + geom_bar(aes(fill=grade))

ramen200_grade$grade <- as.factor(ramen200_grade$grade) %>% relevel("zero")
ramen200_grade %>% ggplot(aes(country)) + geom_bar(stat="count")

ramen200_grade %>% ggplot(aes(country)) + geom_bar()

ramen200_grade %>% ggplot(aes(country, fill=grade)) + geom_bar()

ramen200_grade %>% ggplot(aes(country, fill=grade)) + 
  geom_bar(position = position_stack(reverse = TRUE)) +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE))

ramen200_grade_summ<- ramen200_grade%>%  group_by(country, grade) %>% summarise(gradeCount=n())
ramen200_grade_summ %>% ggplot(aes(country, gradeCount, fill=grade, label=gradeCount)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "fill", stat="identity") +
  geom_text(position = position_fill(vjust = .5), size=3)

Map

World map

map_data() calls various map data. We are trying world map today, which means our canvas is world map.

mymap <- map_data("world")
head(mymap)
ggplot(mymap, aes(x=long, y=lat))

ggplot(mymap, aes(x=long, y=lat)) + 
  geom_map(data = mymap, map = mymap, aes(map_id=region), col = "gray", fill = "white")

mymap<- mymap %>% mutate(lastyear = if_else(region %in% c("USA", "South Korea"), "magenta", "white"))
ggplot(mymap, aes(x=long, y=lat))

mymap %>% ggplot(aes(x=long, y=lat, fill=lastyear, group = group)) +
  geom_map(map = mymap, aes(map_id = region)) + scale_fill_identity() + geom_point(aes(x=100,y=100))
